<paper id="1556560989"><title>Diagnostic model-checking for real-time systems</title><year>1995</year><authors><author org=", Aalborg University" id="2744062252">Kim G. Laxsen</author><author org=", Uppsala University," id="2011261465">Paul Pettersson</author><author org=", Uppsala University," id="2124415778">Wang Yi</author></authors><n_citation>50</n_citation><doc_type /><references><reference>84675887</reference><reference>1488948284</reference><reference>1529601677</reference><reference>1637976039</reference><reference>2101508170</reference><reference>2118802216</reference><reference>2121539168</reference><reference>2160883697</reference><reference>2167668895</reference><reference>2180475648</reference><reference>2344303302</reference><reference>2398303742</reference></references><venue id="" type="">International Hybrid Systems Workshop</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0020977</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.54953">Model checking</keyword><keyword weight="0.45049">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.48919">Automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.44609">Real-time computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.65651">Timed automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.50525">Graphical user interface</keyword><keyword weight="0.5323">Debugging</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Uppaal is a new tool suit for automatic verification of networks of timed automata. In this paper we describe the diagnostic model-checking feature of Uppaal and illustrates its usefulness through the debugging of (a version of) the Philips Audio-Control Protocol. Together with a graphical interface of Uppaal this diagnostic feature allows for a number of errors to be more easily detected and corrected.</abstract></paper>